I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to critically view them as well.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into the things without having to think about where they came from, because back then it wasn't so easy to determine their origin.
We did not question the podium on which we placed them. These parasocial relationships were so important and have influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the show together.
That was completely different from today's streaming, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like it, and people post on social media with "spoiler warnings" or discuss it in closed groups.
Unconsciously, we long for this universal community that once ruled everything.
That's why so many of us are still watching shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," which contained so many one-liners that would be memes today.
We brought all these sayings along, and assumed that most of them already understood them.
Today, one can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads virally on a large scale.
There's far too much of it, and there's no way to systematize it. Will we even be able to get out of this oversaturation again?
We are trapped in a vicious circle, constantly discovering new content, only to realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must hold onto our nostalgia while also accepting that the people who created the works we have liked may also have made significant mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is hard to become rich and powerful without stepping on a few people's toes along the way.
Since we have lost our collective consciousness regarding the media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked when he falls down.
We are in a phase of upheaval, and I am curious to see where it will ultimately lead.
